record_data.record_plain_text: CALPINE MID MERIT, LLC Market-Based Rate Tariff 1. Electric Capacity and Energy. Calpine Mid Merit, LLC ( Seller ) may offer for sale electric capacity and/or energy to Buyer under this FERC Electric Tariff ( Tariff ) from time to time at rates, terms and conditions established by the agreement of the Parties. All such transactions shall be voluntary. 2. Ancillary Services. Seller may offer for sale, in the markets listed below, the following ancillary services to Buyer under this Tariff from time to time at rates, terms and conditions established by the agreement of the Parties. All such transactions shall be voluntary. a. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ( PJM ) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. 3. Third Party Provider. Seller offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 4. Rates. All sales of electric capacity, energy, or ancillary services shall be made at rates established by agreement between Seller and Buyer. 5. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between Seller and Buyer, subject to the terms of this Tariff. 6. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales by Seller, to the extent such sales are subject to the jurisdiction of the Commission and not made pursuant to another tariff or rate schedule on file with the Commission: all wholesale sales of electric energy, capacity and ancillary services. 7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. In Conectiv Mid Merit, LLC, Docket No. ER09-1729-000, the Commission granted Seller the following waivers and blanket authorizations: (a) Waiver of the accounting, reporting, and other requirements of 18 C.F.R. Parts 41 (accounts, records, and memorandum), 101 (uniform system of accounts) and 141 (statement and reports), except Sections 141.14 and 141.15; (b) Waiver of the reporting requirements of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission s regulations, except Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; and (c) Blanket authorization under 18 C.F.R. Part 34 of all future issuances of securities and assumptions of liability; and (d) Waiver of affiliate restrictions in 18 C.F.R. 35.39. 8. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 9. Modifications. Seller may unilaterally apply to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this Tariff under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and the regulations promulgated thereunder. 10. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Northeast region, and a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in all other regions. 11. Effective Date. This Tariff is effective upon acceptance by the Commission.

Basic Easement Payment; Other Easement Payments Basic Easement Payment; Manner of Payment; Separate and Independent . Basic Easement Payment. During the Initial Term and each Renewal Term, if applicable, the Grantee shall pay an annual fixed payment (the Basic Easement Payment ), in advance, to Grantor commencing on the Commencement Date and on the first day of each Easement Year thereafter. Appraisal Process. Two Appraisers. Within fifteen (15) days after the expiration of the Negotiation Period, each Party, at its own cost and expense and by delivering written notice to the other Party, shall appoint a MAI real estate appraiser, with at least five (5) years of full-time appraisal experience with respect to commercial/industrial property located in York County, Pennsylvania, to determine the Fair Market Value. If, within the time period provided for above, only one Party delivers written notice of appointment of a MAI real estate appraiser, such single appraiser appointed shall determine the Fair Market Value. If two (2) appraisers are appointed by the Parties, the two (2) appraisers shall each independently and without consultation with the other appraiser prepare an appraisal of the Fair Market Value within thirty (30) days after their respective appointments. Each appraiser shall seal his/her respective appraisal after completion. Promptly after both appraisals have been completed, the resulting appraisals of the Fair Market Value shall be opened and compared. If the values of the appraisals differ by no more than five percent (5%) of the value of the higher appraisal, then the Fair Market Value shall be the average of the two (2) appraisals. Three Appraisers. If the values of the appraisals differ by more than five percent (5%) of the value of the higher appraisal, then within ten (10) days after the date the appraisals are compared, unless otherwise agreed, the Parties shall jointly appoint a third similarly qualified appraiser. The two (2) appraisers selected by the Parties shall each then submit his/her independent appraisal in simple letter form to the third appraiser stating his/her determination of the Fair Market Value (which determination may not be changed from that which was set forth in such appraiser s sealed appraisal). The sole responsibility of the third appraiser shall be to determine which of the determinations made by the first two (2) appraisers is most accurate. The third appraiser shall have no right to propose a middle ground or any modification of either of the determinations made by the first two (2) appraisers. The third appraiser s choice shall be submitted to Grantor and Grantee within fifteen (15) days after the third appraiser has received the written determination from each of the first two (2) appraisers. The Fair Market Value shall be determined by the selection made by the third appraiser from the determinations submitted by the first two (2) appraisers. Costs. Each Party shall pay the fees and expenses of its own appraiser, and fifty percent (50%) of the fees and expenses of, and the cost of appointing, the third appraiser. Criteria. Subject to the criteria set forth above, the Fair Market Value shall be determined using the market comparison approach. The appraisers shall use their best efforts to fairly and reasonably appraise and determine the Fair Market Value in accordance with the requirements of this Section 4.2, and shall not act as advocates for either Grantor or Grantee. EXHIBIT B-1 DESCRIPTION OF COMMON CIRCULATING WATER SYSTEM PURPOSE AND FUNCTION PURPOSE The purpose of the circulating water system is to provide a heat sink for the steam cycle used in Unit 4 of the York 1 Plant. When the York 2 Plant is complete, this system will also be used as a heat sink for the steam cycle of Unit 7. FUNCTION The function of the circulating water system is to remove heat from various heat exchangers by the circulation of cooling water from the Susquehanna River. SCOPE The scope of this system for the York 1 Plant, Unit 4 encompasses: 1. Two (2) circulating water pumps 2. One (1) auxiliary circulating water pumps 3. Blowdown header 4. Makeup water system 5. One (1) 10-cell, induced draft cooling towers 6. Circulating water chemical treatment system 7. Valves, piping, and instrumentation for the equipment heat exchangers, including the main condenser Note, Bullet 3 and 4 will be common to both the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant. DESIGN PHILOSOPHY The circulating water system is designed to provide a heat sink for the main condenser for Steam turbine generators associated with Unit 4 and Unit 7. TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION Blowdown and Makeup Flow Because the cooling tower uses evaporation for its primary means of heat removal, dissolved contaminants accumulate in the system. Cooling tower blowdown is used to control the amount of contaminants to a level that will not form deposits on heat exchange surfaces. Cooling tower blowdown continually directs a portion of the circulating water system back to the Susquehanna River. It should be noted that the blowdown is isolated when the tower basin is being chemically treated. The 12-inch cooling tower blowdown line tees off the York 1 Plant circulating water pump discharge header before any components are supplied with water. It is provided with a root valve, check valve and a pneumatically actuated butterfly valve. The blowdown water is discharged to the Susquehanna River. This blowdown header will be common to the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant. A river water makeup system is provided to maintain level in Unit 4 cooling tower basin and replenish water lost through blowdown evaporation and drift. When the York 2 Plant expansion project is complete, the makeup system will also be used to replenish water lost through evaporation in the Unit 7 cooling tower basin. Currently, the York 1 Plant utilizes two (2) x 50% capacity makeup water pumps. These pumps take suction from a wetwell below the pump house operating floor. The wetwell is fed from the Susquehanna River through two (2) 18 underground supply lines fitted with sluice gates SGV-1/2 at the wet well wall for isolation. Each 18 fill header has a pair of 2mm wedge wire screens ME-2NB1/2 in the Susquehanna River designed to be environmentally friendly. Each makeup water pump discharge has an expansion joint, discharge check valve, and motor operated butterfly valve V-4A/B/C, which feed to the 24 makeup water header. The 24 header has an 8 surge-suppression valve V-36 that discharges back to the wetwell in the event of pressure surges associated with sudden line rupture. The makeup water discharge pipeline runs from the pump house and contains four (4) air surge valves located in manholes along the pipe routing. The automatic valves are designed to remove air trapped in the system on restart after extended shutdowns or system draining. From the makeup water pump house, the piping system runs underground. The pipeline enters the site from the north perimeter. At that point, a 12 tap is installed to provide suction to the fire pump house. The makeup system is the primary water source for fire suppression water at flows greater than 2000 gpm and is capable of providing suction flow to both fire pumps. This header for the York 1 Plant is reduced to a 16-inch header for the Unit 4 cooling tower, prior to entering the Chemical Addition Building. In this building, the makeup water line feeds the Unit 4 cooling tower basin through individual air-operated butterfly valves. A separate 16-inch header will be used to supply the Unit 7 cooling tower basin. As stated above, this makeup and blowdown system will be common to the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant. The only addition to the system will be a third makeup water pump to support the York 2 Plant. The location and switchgear for this third pump was already designed into the existing pump house. COMMON COMPONENT DESCRIPTION Makeup Water Pumps The circulating water makeup system serves Unit 4 and is comprised of two (2) 50% capacity makeup water pumps. The pumps are located in the makeup water pump house and take suction from the Susquehanna River. A third pump will be added for the York 2 Plant. Each pump is rated for 4,060 gpm at 228 feet discharge head, and sized to provide the necessary makeup water to one cooling tower. Check valves on each pump discharge line prevent reverse pump rotation and excessive water loss when the pump is secured and other makeup water pumps are operating. The makeup water pumps (P-1A/B/C) are vertical, centrifugal, three-stage pumps manufactured by Flowserve, Model 16ENH. The pump bowls and impellers are constructed of Cd4MCu. The pump shaft is Nitronic 50. The column is constructed of Type 316 stainless steel. The makeup water pumps contain addition column, enclosing tube, and shaft sections since the motor and pump operating floors are on separate levels of the pump house. The makeup water pumps are each driven by a 350 hp, 4000 VAC, 1,800 rpm motor manufactured by Hitachi. COMMON CONTROLS DESCRIPTION Makeup Water Pump Control The makeup water pumps are controlled automatically by the DCS or may be started locally at load center in the makeup pump house electrical building. The pumps are powered from 4160 V AC. A pump will start if: The pump is selected by the DCS to operate, or The hand switch at the pump breaker is positioned to close, or The pump is started manually through the DCS, or An auto start signal is received from the DCS, or The fire system calls for river water for fire suppression onsite or The pump is selected by the DCS to be the next pump for running and an operating pump trips. A pump will trip if: A stop signal (auto or manual) is received from the DCS, or The hand switch at the pump breaker is positioned to open, or The static trip device trips the motor., or Both makeup water control valves are closed, or Wet well level decreases to 5 inches COMMON EQUIPMENT DATA Makeup Water Pumps (P-A/B/C) Quantity 3

EXHIBIT B-2 DESCRIPTION OF COMMON FIRE PROTECTION SYSTEM PURPOSE AND FUNCTION PURPOSE The purpose of the fire protection system is to provide fire detection and suppression in areas of the plant. SCOPE The scope of the fire protection system consists of the following: Water Treatment Building Fire Pump House River water pump house DESIGN PHILOSOPHY The fire protection system is designed for continuous, full-time, on-demand operation. The York Energy Center fire system design pressure is sufficient to meet the highest flow demand (1,760 gpm at 70 psig) or the highest discharge pressure required at an end point anywhere in the fire protection system (200 gpm at 65 psig). YORK ENERGY CENTER UNDERGROUND FIRE MAIN SYSTEM Flow Description The York Energy Center Units firepumps can be supplied from two separate sources: a primary connection from the river water and a back-up connection from the Filtered water tank. The York Energy Center Fire Pumps, 0-KC-P-001A and 0-KC-P-001B, take suction from the river water forwarding pumps. If the river water is not available or if the demand is too high, the fire pumps will take suction from the service water tank. Flow from the fire pumps feed a 12 pressurized main, which loops the site. Pressure in the main will be held at 150 psi. Major Component Description Main Fire Pumps (0-KC-P-00IA) and (0-KC-P-001B) The two main Fire Pumps are horizontal split case, end suction centrifugal pump, manufactured by Peerless, Model 6AEF14Q The pump has a capacity of 2000 gpm at a TDH of 231 feet. The pump is driven by a 480 V ac, 1800 rpm, 150 hp open drip-proof motor, manufactured by Emerson. The pump has a cast iron casing, stainless steel shaft and a bronze impeller. Jockey Fire Pump (0-KC-P-003) The jockey fire pump is a single stage, wet end pre-assembled centrifugal pump manufactured by Peerless, Model 1X1.5-8STP 8196. The jockey pump has a capacity of 50 gpm at a TDH of 231 feet.. The pump is driven by a 230/480V ac, 3546rpm, 15hp motor. The normal suction for the jockey pump is the Service Water Tank MOV- 912 MOV-912 is a 12 inch motor operated butterfly valve used to isolate the Service water tank from the river water make-up system. MOV-912 may be opened in the event the river water make-up pumps are out of service to provide a secondary source of water to the main fire pump suction. MOV-912 can be opened remotely from the DCS, locally from the motor and manually at the valve itself. MOV-912 is located in the fire water pumphouse and is powered from power panel 0KC-PDPFPH. Administration Building / Shop/ Water Treatment Wet Pipe Fire Systems The administration building, shop area and portions of the water Treatment building are protected by a wet pipe fire protection system. The piping on a wet system is always fully charged and water flow ids controlled by fusible links in the sprinkler heads. If temperature in a protected area exceeds 200F, the fusible links will melt and initiate water flow. The system is monitored by flow switches that will give alarm if flow is detected. Fire Pump House Fire Alarm System The Fire Pump House is monitored by a fire alarm system only. No fixed fire suppression system is installed. The fire alarm system consists of two Notifier addressable manual pull stations, two Notifier analog ionization detectors and two Notifier weatherproof fire alarm audible/strobes. Make-up water pumphouse The Make-Up Water Pumphouse is monitored by a fire alarm system only. No fixed fire suppression system is installed. The fire alarm system consists of four Notifier addressable manual pull stations, Three- Notifier analog ionization detectors and three Notifier weatherproof fire alarm strobes. Common Instrumentation and Control Description Fire Pump Control The main fire pump controllers are full voltage starting electric fire pump controllers with power transfer switches manufactured by Firetrol. Fire pump 0-KC-P-00IA is normally powered from transformer 4EC-XFRA3 with an emergency supply from 4EC-XFRB3. Fire pump 0-KC-P-001B is normally powered from 4EC-XFRB3 with an emergency supply from 4EC-XFRA3. The motor controller will transfer automatically to the emergency source on a loss of primary feed. The motor controller will automatically transfer back to it normal power supply once it has been restored, or if desired, it may be transferred back manually at the controller. The main fire pumps can be started manually or automatically. Manual starting is accomplished at the local control panel or remotely at fire panel MFPA-1, located in the control room. The pump is operated as follows: Manually, by a start button, located on the Pump Controller that activates the motor circuit or by a remote key switch located in the Control Room on fire panel MFAP-1. After manual starting, the motor can be stopped by pressing the stop button on the pump controller. Automatically, when low fire main pressure (50 psig) is sensed by the pressure switch in the pump controller. Once started automatically, the pump will run for a minimum of 10 minutes following the reestablishment of normal system pressure. The main fire pumps may also be stopped manually by pressing the stop button on the controller at any time during the minimum run timer operation. Jockey Fire Pump Control When in Automatic, the jockey fire pump is controlled by a pressure switch through the local control cabinet. When fire system pressure decreases to approximately 75 psig the jockey pump will start to reestablish normal system pressure. The jockey pump may also be started manually by placing the Hand-Off-Auto switch to ON. The jockey fire pump may be stopped manually by placing the switch to OFF. EXHIBIT B-3 DESCRIPTION OF COMMON FUEL GAS SYSTEM Fuel gas is supplied to the York Energy Center via a dedicated lateral from a Transco natural gas pipeline. A 16 gas main is routed from a Transco substation located south of the site. This 16 supply line reduces to a 12 line, which then feeds the natural gas regulator house for the York 1 Plant. A coalescing filter and pressure control valve stations condition the fuel gas, which leaves the natural gas regulator house in a 16-inch supply header. Each York 1 Plant combustion turbine is then fed from the 16-inch header through an 8-inch gas train supply line. Each gas train filters, heats and meters the gas to its respective combustion turbine (CT1, CT2 and CT3). The combustion turbine fuel gas equipment filters and controls the flow of gas to the burners. The only component of the system common to both York 1 Plant and York 2 Plant will be the dedicated Transco lateral pipeline and the Transco substation. A branch connection will supply a natural gas compressor and subsequently the combustion turbines (CT5 and CT6), duct burners (HRSG5 and HRSG6) and auxiliary boiler for the York 2 Plant. Dedicated custody and heat content metering will be provided for the York 2 Plant natural gas. EXHIBIT B-4 DESCRIPTION OF COMMON FUEL OIL SYSTEM PURPOSE AND FUNCTION PURPOSE The main fuel oil system transfers fuel oil from the fuel oil storage tank to the combustion turbines. FUNCTION The function of the York 1 Plant main fuel oil system is to: 1. Transfer fuel oil from the supply trucks to the fuel oil storage tank via four (4) fuel oil unloading pumps in two (2) truck bays. 2. Transfer fuel oil from the fuel oil storage tank to the combustion turbine fuel oil skids 3. Remove foreign particles from fuel oil prior to the combustion turbine fuel oil burners 4. Store fuel oil for use in the combustion turbines when the primary fuel (natural gas) is not available Bullet 1 and 4 are the functions that will be common to both the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant. SCOPE The common functions of the main fuel oil system comprise the following: One fuel oil storage tank Fuel oil unloading pumps DESIGN PHILOSOPHY The main fuel oil system is a common system that supplies fuel oil to units 1, 2, and 3 combustion turbines for use in the burners and returns any unused fuel to the storage tank. This system will also be utilized to supply fuel oil to units 5 and 6 combustion turbines as part of the York 2 Plant Expansion Project. The fuel oil supplied to the combustion turbine burners is conditioned by pressurizing and filtering as necessary to promote efficient combustion. The main fuel oil system metallurgy is primarily carbon steel. The handling and transfer of fuel oil do not present a corrosion problem in the piping. TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION The main fuel oil system consists of one fuel oil storage tank supplying a common header. From the common header, fuel oil transfer pumps will supply fuel oil to the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant combustion turbines. The fuel oil injection skids at each combustion turbine provide fuel to the burners to meet the load requirements and return the remainder to the storage tank. Fuel Oil unloading pumps will transfer fuel oil from supply trucks to the storage tank. COMMON COMPONENT DESCRIPTION Fuel Oil Storage Tank (0-JC-T-001A) The fuel oil tank is located south of unit 1 combustion turbine. The tank has a capacity of 4,000,000 gallons. The tank physical dimensions are 120 feet in diameter and 48 feet high. The fuel oil tank is a double-walled tank with a nominal three-foot space between the inner and outer tanks in order to provide secondary containment in the event of a tank failure. The outer tank is designed to contain 110% of the full contents of the inner fuel oil tank. Fuel Oil Unloading Pumps (0-JC-P-002A, -002B, -002C, & -002D) The fuel oil unloading pumps are single-stage horizontal motor-driven, centrifugal pumps. The pumps are manufactured by Flowserve Corporation. The pump is a Model I 2K4x3 82RV M3 ST. The fuel oil transfer pump capacity is 400 gpm at 70 ft TDH. The motor is rated 15.0 hp at 3,600 rpm. The power supply required is 460 V ac, three-phase, 60-cycle service. COMMON INSTRUMENTATION AND CONTROL DESCRIPTION The main fuel oil system is normally controlled by the automatic startup and shutdown controls associated with the combustion turbines. The system also has limited remote control capability. Fuel Oil Storage Tank The fuel oil tank has a level transmitter, JC-LT-018A, which provides input for control and instrumentation both locally and remotely. Local tank level can be read on a 0 - 100 percent full gauge. The level transmitter inputs a dc signal to provide a low level alarm at 72 inches, and a low-low level alarm at 36 inches. Currently, the low-low level trips the York 1 Plant fuel oil transfer pumps and the fuel oil injection skids. The trip signal will result in a combustion turbine trip. The level transmitter also provides a high level alarm at 573.5 inches. The tank level alarms can be read at the DCS through the BOP panel to the DCS interface, and at the SOP panel in the electrical enclosure. Fuel Oil Unloading Pumps The fuel oil unloading pumps are operated from a local control panel, with START/STOP features and running indication. The pumps are equipped with local suction and discharge pressure indication. EQUIPMENT DATA Fuel Oil Storage Tank Qty. 1

EXHIBIT B-5 DESCRIPTION OF COMMON MAIN POWER DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM PURPOSE AND FUNCTION PURPOSE The purpose of the main power distribution system at York Energy Center is to step up the generator output voltage for remote distribution via the PECO Peach Bottom South Substation. FUNCTION The main power distribution system for the York 1 Plant is composed of: Isolated phase bus Generator circuit breakers -GCB1, GCB2, GCB3, and GCB4, Main transformers -T1, T2, T3, and T 4 500kV Air Insulated Bus 500kV circuit breaker 501 and its associated disconnect and ground switches The function of the main generator and generator excitation systems is to convert mechanical energy produced by the gas turbine or steam turbine into electrical energy. The electrical energy is then fed to step-up transformers T1, T2, T3, and T 4, via their respective generator circuit breakers and Isolated Phase Bus systems. The Main Transformers step-up the voltage from the generated voltage - 13.8 kV for the combustion turbine generators and 18 kV for the steam turbine generators -for distribution at 500 kV. The output from Units 1-4 step up transformers feeds into the 500 kV Air Insulated Bus and then to the 500kv line Breaker 501. The combined power is exported to the PECO Peach Bottom 500 kV Substation via a short transmission line for commercial distribution. Likewise, the York 2 Plant electrical energy will be fed to step-up transformers T5, T6 and T7, via their respective generator circuit breakers and Isolated Phase Bus systems. The output from Units 5-7 step up transformers will feed into the 500 kV Air Insulated Bus and then to a 500kv Line Breaker. After the York 2 Plant 500 kV Line Breaker the power will be connected to the existing 5034 transmission line and exported to the PECO Peach Bottom Substation. SCOPE The functions common to the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant of the main 500kv distribution system comprise of the following: ( Calpine 5034 line distributing 500kv to Peach Bottom South Substation. DESIGN PHILOSOPHY The 500kv transmission line designated 5034 will be common to the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant for the distribution of power to the Peach Bottom Substation. TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM DESCRIPTION In general, the generators associated with the York 1 Plant use the mechanical energy supplied by the gas turbines/steam turbine and convert it to electrical energy. From the generator, the power is transmitted via the isolated phase bus and generator circuit breaker to the main step-up transformers. The combustion turbine generator main transformers, T1, T2, and T3 convert the 13.8 kV output to 500 kV. The Unit 4 steam turbine generator main transformer, T4, converts the 18 kV output to 500 kV. Units 1-4 step up transformers output feed into the 500 kV Air Insulated Bus and then to 500 kV line Breaker 501. The combined power is exported to the PECO Peach Bottom 500kV South substation via a short transmission line (5034) for commercial distribution. EXHIBIT B-6 DESCRIPTION OF COMMON WASTEWATER TREATMENT SYSTEM PURPOSE AND FUNCTION PURPOSE The purpose of the wastewater treatment system is to treat Units 1 through 7 plant aqueous wastes and dispose of the compliant effluent into the Susquehanna River. The effluent shall comply with the limits permitted by local and federal environmental regulatory agencies. Heat recovery steam generator ( HRSG ) blow down shall be collected separately, quenched with circulating water and discharged to the circulating water system. FUNCTION The function of the wastewater treatment system is to collect low volume liquid waste generated by Units 1 through 7 at a central location (wastewater treatment area) and adjust the pH to a range of 6 to 9. The waste is then discharged to the cooling tower and to the Susquehanna River via the blowdown line. HRSG blow down shall be collected in the HRSG blow down sumps, quenched with circulating water and discharged to the respective circulating water system for each of the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant. SCOPE The Units 1 through 7 wastewater treatment common systems are comprised of the following major components: Water Treatment Building Sump Water Treatment Building Sump Pumps Filter Backwash Sump Filter Backwash Sump Pumps Wastewater Neutralization Tank Waste Neutralization Transfer Pumps Wastewater Holdup Tank Wastewater Holdup Transfer Pumps Sulfuric Acid Storage Tank Sulfuric Acid Metering Pumps Caustic Storage Tank Caustic Metering Pumps DESIGN PHILOSOPHY The wastewater treatment system is designed to handle an average of 43,200 gallons per day, to a maximum (short duration) instantaneous rate of 100 gallons per minute, of wastewater from Units 1 through 7. Local area sumps are utilized to collect floor and equipment drains and convey the wastewater to the water treatment waste sump. Each sump is furnished with two (2) 100 percent capacity submersible centrifugal sump pumps. The water treatment building sump is utilized to collect the discharge from the oil/water separators of each of the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant and any effluent from the water treatment building equipment hubs and floor drains. Two 100-percent-capacity centrifugal sump pumps are used to transfer the effluent to the waste neutralization system. Two 100-percent-capacity centrifugal pumps are used for waste neutralization transfer pumps. The pumps are located in the water treatment building. Mixing tees are provided for In-line mixing of acid and caustic with the wastewater stream. Both mixing tees are identical. Check valves are installed upstream of the mixing tees to prevent backflow. The mixing tees are designed to ensure turbulent flow for good mixing with minimum hot spots. An in-tank mixing eductor is used in conjunction with neutralization pump recirculation to thoroughly mix the waste neutralization tank water for proper pH adjustment. Once the pH is within the limits the effluent is pumped to the wastewater hold up tank. Two 100-percent-capacity centrifugal pumps are used for wastewater holdup tank transfer pumps. The pumps are located in the water treatment building. A pH meter is located at the suction of this pump skid to monitor pH and to reroute the wastewater from the wastewater holdup tank to the waste neutralization tank if the pH of the waste water is not within limits before it s to discharge into the river. The allowable limits for discharge of wastewater into the Susquehanna River are 50 mg/l for oil, 100 mg/l for suspended solids, and a pH of 6 to 9. The filter backwash sump and pumps are located in the Water treatment building. This system receives discharge water from the ultrafiltration, reverse osmosis system, continuous-deionization system, and waste water holdup tank. This sump is furnished with two (2) 100 percent submersible centrifugal sump pumps which convey the water to the unit 4 of unit 7 cooling tower basins. The water treatment building sump includes two (2), 100% capacity sump pumps which convey its contents to the neutralization tank. The water treatment building sump is also used to convey RO and CDI cleaning waste, which may require pH adjustment, to the neutralization tank. The wastewater holdup tank serves as the central collection point for plant wastewater and receives treated wastewater from the oil/water separator and the neutralization tank. Two (2), 100% capacity wastewater holdup transfer pumps are used to convey wastewater from the holdup tank to Filter Backwash Sump. Non-compliant wastewater is automatically recycled from the holdup tank to the neutralization tank. The neutralization tank receives wastewater requiring pH adjustment prior to discharge to the waste water hold up tank and the Filter Backwash Sump. Acid and/or caustic are injected into the recirculating waste stream for pH adjustment. Neutralized waste is transferred to the wastewater holdup tank via the waste neutralization transfer pumps for subsequent discharge to the Filter Backwash Sump. EXHIBIT B-7 DESCRIPTION OF COMMON WATER TREATMENT SYSTEM PURPOSE AND FUNCTION PURPOSE The purpose of the water treatment system is to filter raw water from the Susquehanna River to maintain level in the Service Water Tank and to purify Service Water to meet the demineralized water requirements of York Energy Center Units 1 through 7. These requirements are given in Appendix B. FUNCTION The function of the water treatment system is to receive raw water from the Susquehanna River and filter with pressurized membrane ultrafiltration to produce service water with satisfactory dissolved solids to feed the double pass reverse osmosis (R.O.) systems and continuous deionization (CDI) systems to produce demineralized water. The demineralized water is forwarded to the demineralized water storage tank for subsequent use as HRSG makeup water, combustion turbine NOx water and combustion turbine inlet air fogging. SCOPE The water treatment systems which are common to the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant are comprised of the following major components: One (1) 200,000 gallon Raw Water Storage Tank One (1) 300,000 gallon Service Water Tank One (1) 4 MMgal Demineralized Water Tank Three (2) Raw Water Forwarding Pumps Three (3) Filtered Water Forwarding Pumps Four (4) Ultra Filtration Units Four (4) RO Units Two (2) CDI Units One (1) RO / CDI PLC Control System One (1) UF PLC Control System DESIGN PHILOSOPHY The demineralized water quality requirements in Appendix B are based upon meeting the HRSG feedwater, steam turbine and combustion turbine water requirements. The water treatment system is designed to receive river water of the quality specified in Appendix A and produce demineralized water of the quality specified in Appendix B at a rate of 700 gpm for each of the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant. The complete demineralizer system is installed in the Water Treatment Building. The system is constructed of heavy duty, industrial type components, with the majority of the equipment factory skid mounted on structural steel framing. River Water from the Susquehanna River maintains level in the 200,000 gallon Raw Water Tank outside of the Water Treatment Building. Raw water enters the water treatment building through a 10-inch header from which the Raw Water Forwarding Pumps take suction. The raw water pressure is boosted by the Raw Water Forwarding Pumps up to 60 psig and conveyed to the rotating basket strainer for initial filtration then to each of the 350 gpm rated Memcor Ultra Filtration Units to maintain level in the service water tank. Filtered Water from the Ultra Filtration Units discharges to the 300,000 Service Water Tank outside of the Water Treatment Building. Filtered water enters the water treatment building through a 10-inch header from which the Filtered Water Forwarding Pumps take suction. The filtered water pressure is boosted by the Filtered Water Forwarding Pumps up to 90 psig and conveyed to the four (4) 184 gpm rated Reverse Osmosis Units. Final polishing is performed by two (2) CDI units. It is important to note that one (1) complete water treatment train consisting of two (2) UF s, two (2) RO s and one (1) CDI was added as part of the York Block 2 expansion project to increase the water treatment capacity from the original 350 gpm to the 700 gpm noted above. TECHNICAL DESCRIPTION FLOW DESCRIPTION Refer to Altran P&ID DE-100-E-MD1016 SH3 and Siemens P & ID s 0D140-9100 Sheets 1 - 14. Water Treatment System Raw water is supplied to the 200,000 gallon Raw Water Storage Tank via one, 10-inch line. Raw water is supplied to the water treatment building via one, 10-inch line. The three (3) raw water forwarding pumps take suction from the 10-inch raw water supply header and discharge to a common 8-inch manifold. Two (2) 100% capacity rotating basket strainers cartridge filters are fed from the discharge of the raw water forwarding pumps followed by four (4) 350 gpm Ultra Filtration Units which discharge to the 300,000 gallon Service Water Tank . A separate connection comes off the raw water pump discharge header to feed mobile demineralizer trailer feed stations located in the water treatment building. After passing through the Ultra Filtration Units the water is discharged to the 300,000 gallon Service Water Tank. Service Water is supplied to the water treatment building via one, 10-inch line. The three (2) filtered water forwarding pumps take suction from the 10-inch raw water supply header and discharge to a common 8-inch manifold to the demineralized water trains for each of the York 1 Plant and the York 2 Plant which discharges to the common 4,000,000 gallon demineralized water storage tank. The filter backwash sump is equipped with two (2) 100% capacity vertical sump pumps. The sump pumps discharge into a common header and convey filter backwash water, RO, and CDI concentrate to the Unit 4 or Unit 7 Circulating water systems. The demineralized water storage tanks supply water to the demineralized water forwarding pumps. The Service Water Booster Pumps take suction from the Service Water Tank and discharge to a common header to support pump seal applications, sodium hypochlorite educator motive force, and washdown stations. Demineralized Water Storage System The demineralized water forwarding pumps for each block take suction from the common 4,000,000 gallon storage tank via individual pump suction headers. . MAJOR COMPONENT DESCRIPTION Raw Water Forwarding Pumps There are two (2) Raw Water Forwarding Pumps. The 580 gpm (130 ft) pumps are horizontal, centrifugal type manufactured by Flowserve, Model 2K4x3-13RV M3 ST. The pump motors are 40 hp, 1,800 rpm, fed 480 VAC. The pump casing, and shaft are 316 stainless steel. Shaft sealing is provided by a cartridge style mechanical seal. Filtered Water Forwarding Pumps There are two (3) Filtered Water Forwarding Pumps. The 572 gpm (153 ft) pumps are horizontal, centrifugal type manufactured by Flowserve, Model 2K4x3-13RV M3 ST. The pump motors are 50 hp, 1,800 rpm, fed 480 VAC. The pump casing, and shaft are 316 stainless steel. Shaft sealing is provided by a cartridge style mechanical seal. INSTRUMENTATION AND CONTROLS Water Treatment System Instrumentation and Control The Ultra Filtration (UF) System and RO / CDI systems are controlled by separate PLC s with individual HMI s. The PLC control systems are complete with a supervisory control and human-machine interface (HMI). The HMI s are located in a free-standing controls panel inside the water treatment building electronics room. There is a connection from the RO PLC to plant DCS allowing remote monitoring of the Water Treatment systems from the Control Room. A detailed description of the water treatment system control system, and information regarding set-points and control logic, can be obtained from the Siemens Water Technologies RO and UF system operation and maintenance manuals.
